Part 3. Regularization

Introdution to regularization

regualrization . small n, large p least square estimation . , regularization procedure penalty function Y . , . penalty function . ,

  1. Ridge penalty \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = \underset{\boldsymbol{\beta}}{\arg\min}{\left(\parallel Y-X\boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel ^2_2 + \lambda \parallel \boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel^2_2 \right) } \]
  1. () .
  2. <> 0 ( ).
  1. Lasso penalty (1996) \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}=\underset{\boldsymbol{\beta}}{\arg\min}\left(\parallel Y-X\boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel_2^2 + \lambda \parallel \boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel_1 \right) \]
  1. () .
  2. <> , ( ).
  3. <> small n, large p n .
  1. Elastic-net (2005) \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}=\underset{\beta}{\arg\min}\left(\parallel Y-X\boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel_2^2 + \lambda[ (1-\alpha) \parallel \boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel_2^2/2 + \alpha \parallel \boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel_1 ] \right) \]
  1. () Ridge Lasso , .
  2. <> tuning parameter (\(\lambda \text{ and } \boldsymbol{\alpha}\)) .
  1. Group lasso (2007) \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}=\underset{\beta}{\arg\min} \left( \frac{1}{2}\parallel Y-\sum_{\ell=1}^{L} X_\ell\boldsymbol{\beta_\ell} \parallel_2^2 + \lambda \sum_{\ell=1}^{L}\sqrt{p_\ell} \parallel \boldsymbol{\beta_\ell} \parallel_2 \right) \]
  • Group selection .
  1. Sparse group lasso (2011) \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}=\underset{\beta}{\arg\min}\left( \frac{1}{2}\parallel Y-\sum_{\ell=1}^{L}X_\ell\boldsymbol{\beta_\ell} \parallel_2^2 + \lambda[ (1-\alpha) \sum_{\ell=1}^{L}\sqrt{p_\ell}\parallel \boldsymbol{\beta_\ell} \parallel_2 + \alpha \parallel \boldsymbol{\beta} \parallel_1 ] \right) \]
  • Group selection .
  1. etc

The Lasso

Fitting the lasso model with alpha=1

fit.lasso <- glmnet(x, y, alpha=1, nlambda=10, family="gaussian")
fit.lasso

## [10,] 439 0.9983   9.039
  • nlambda: recommended to be 100 or more.
  • Df: the number of nonzero coefficients.
  • %dev: the percent deviance explained (for gaussian, this is the R-square).
  • Deviance: the difference of 2*log-likelihood between saturated model and current model.
  • Lambda: the corresponding value of lambda.

  • lambda.min: the value which gives minumum mean cross-validated error (like mse).

Elastic-net with alpha\(\in(0, 1)\)

  • Distinct advantages of elastic-net
  • Grouping selection
  • When n<<p, we can select variables up to p

Selecting the tuning parameters (alpha, lambda)

set.seed(1234)
foldid <- sample(rep(1:10, length=length(y)))

Cross-validation with two tuning parameters

alpha.grid <- seq(0, 1, 0.1)
cv.enet <- as.list( 1:length(alpha.grid) )
for( h in 1:length(alpha.grid) ){
  cv.enet[[h]] <- cv.glmnet(x, y2, family="binomial", type.measure="dev",
                            alpha=alpha.grid[h], nlambda=15, 
                            foldid=foldid)
}
# save(cv.enet, alpha.grid, file="[object]cv.enet.RData")
load("[object]cv.enet.RData")
cv.enet.cvm <- NULL
for( h in 1:length(cv.enet)){
  cv.enet.cvm <- cbind(cv.enet.cvm, cv.enet[[h]]$cvm)
}
dimnames(cv.enet.cvm) <- list( paste0("lambda.",1:14), paste0("alpha.",1:11) )

opt.tune <- which( cv.enet.cvm == min(cv.enet.cvm), arr.ind=TRUE )
opt.tune
##          row col
## lambda.3   3   2
opt.alpha <- alpha.grid[ opt.tune[2] ]
opt.lambda.min <- cv.enet[[ opt.tune[2] ]]$lambda.min
opt.lambda.1se <- cv.enet[[ opt.tune[2] ]]$lambda.1se

c(opt.alpha=opt.alpha, opt.lambda.min=opt.lambda.min, opt.lambda.1se=opt.lambda.1se)
##      opt.alpha opt.lambda.min opt.lambda.1se 
##      0.1000000      0.6943505      0.9647969

  • we must use the same foldid so that we compare the results for each alpha.

  • You should investigate the alpha less than 0.1.

Penalty factors

  • If we consider the variable known to be associated with response variable, we involve them as covariates in the model.

Generating arbitrary covariates

cov1 <- NULL
cov1[y2==0] <- rbinom(sum(y2==0), 1, prob=0.8)
cov1[y2==1] <- rbinom(sum(y2==1), 1, prob=0.4)
table(y2, cov1)
##    cov1
## y2    0   1
##   0  38 147
##   1 109  76
cov2 <- NULL
cov2[y2==0] <- rpois(sum(y2==0), lambda=40)
cov2[y2==1] <- rpois(sum(y2==1), lambda=60)
boxplot(cov2~y2)

x.cov <- cbind(cov1, cov2, x)

pf <- c(0, 0, rep(1,ncol(x)) )
table(pf)
## pf
##     0     1 
##     2 15000
pf.fit <- glmnet(x.cov, y2, family="binomial", penalty.factor = pf, nlambda=10 )
pf.fit
## 
## Call:  glmnet(x = x.cov, y = y2, family = "binomial", nlambda = 10,      penalty.factor = pf) 
## 
##       Df   %Dev    Lambda
